    "### Data overview\n",
    "\n",
    "The \"ideal\" dataset that we would be looking for should contain information like instructor ratings, average course grades, number of students enrolled, and a measurement of their workload. Variables like average grade and instructor ratings will be continuous, along with discrete variables such as the amount of students enrolled, and what course they are enrolled in. We will be looking at data from the 2022 Fall quarter to 2023 Spring quarter via CAPE evaluations which are publically available. The data would be stored in a table grouped by the course id / course name, and for each of these we would have data containing the average grades received, instructor recommending rates, course workloads, and drop rates. Some datasets that already exist include CAPE Evals. These are stored as URLs, and are publically available to everyone. Another public student made dataset exists in Github, containing data recorded from webreg, which include the times at which students dropped or enrolled in the class.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Dataset #1\n",
    "  - Name: capes_data.csv (raw), capes_clean.csv (processed)\n",
    "  - Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sanbornpnguyen/ucsdcapes\n",
    "  - Number of observations: 63363 (raw), 81 (processed)\n",
    "  - Number of variables: 11 (raw), 5 (processed)\n",
    "  - Variables most relevant to the project: we will be focusing on the variables \"Percentage Recommended Professor\", \"Study Hours per Week\", and \"Average Grade Received\". The \"Percentage Recommended Professor\" is a percentage that stands for what proportion of the CAPEs would recommend the professor (not the course itself), which is the instructor rating. The \"Studys Hours per Week\" gives float data to two decimal places on the average study hours per week among the CAPEs, in other words, the workload. The \"Average Grade Received\" variable is for the actual average grade that the CAPEs received on this course, both in the form of letter grade and a more detailed two decimal place GPA out of 4.\n",
    "  - Shortcomings: It must be admitted that not everyone enrolled in the course responded on the CAPE, which may cause the dataset less representative to the actual entire course situation.\n",
    "\n",
    "&nbsp;\n",
    "- Dataset #2\n",
    "  - Name: enroll_clean.csv (processed) (original data consist of multiple datasets)\n",
    "  - Link: https://github.com/UCSD-Historical-Enrollment-Data/UCSDHistEnrollData\n",
    "  - Number of observations: 400536 (processed)\n",
    "  - Number of variables: 5 (raw), 7 (processed)\n",
    "  - Variables most relevant to the project: we will mostly be focusing on the variable \"enrolled\" and \"waitlisted\". \"Enrolled\" displays integer numbers of the currently enrolled number of people to the course over time. \"Waitlisted\" displays the integer numbers of the currently waitlisted number of people to the course over time. We will monitor their changes from the beginning of the quarter to the end of week 4 - when the \"drop\" action ends. Everytime the \"waitlisted\" number decreases by 1 from the beginning of instruction to the end of week 2 (the last day of waitlist), we count it as 1 person dropping, because that's when waitlist automatically fills the enrollment in once a spot is available. From week 3 to the end of week 4, everytime the \"enrolled\" number decreases by 1, we count it as 1 person dropping, because waitlist has already ended and people only drop out from the course.\n",
    "  - Shortcomings: Since the dataset only provides the changes of enrollment and waitlist number over the time, but not directly showing when the \"drop\" action happens, we can only infer drop data from the changes of enrollment and waitlist, which may not be too precise. We need to assume that most of people stay on the waitlist for the first two weeks."
   ]
